arch:note.arch:string: The purpose of the daily journal was to record the activities taking place in a trench each day. This included which loci were excavated, how and why loci were excavated and the ongoing impressions of the relationships among loci. It should be noted that journals record the actions, impressions and ideas of trench supervisors during the excavations. They are not, therefore, the final interpretations or syntheses of the emerging data.

arch:internalDocument.arch:string:
Daily Trench Journal

Area F, Trench 7

June 19, 2005

C. Painter

Today the majority of concentration was paid to fill locus 7211 in order to better trace both walls 7209 and 7212 along with mud brick platform 7183 in the southeast corner of the trench which was found to continue with another course of yellow unburned bricks. Work in 7211, which was carried out with small hand picks and trowels, uncovered a number of new features including another small pit feature with pot sherds lining the interior which is filled with a tightly-compacted pebble/granule fill (7218), a cluster of medium-sized cobbles arranged in an ovoid shape (7217), and another surface that was designated as L7219.

This surface is mud plastered and was subsequently burnt as there are ash and charcoal inclusions. In the center of the surface is a sunken pit, measuring 55 x 55 x 3-5cm in depth. This pit is also plastered therefore it was included within this locus. The floor is burnt with the heaviest concentration of burning in the sunken pit area (fire pit?). On the eastern side, the floor slopes up to meet an in situ door socket that has been sunk into the surface in the northeast corner of the locus.

Surface 7208 was also finished being excavated using the Household Archaeology Protocol in which all buckets were counted and sieved. In total, the amount of surface that was included within locus 7208 came to 189 liters.

Also in examining the section profile of wall 7202, which is visible in the interior of closed pit locus 7162, a very thin (<5cm) surface layer was noticed that extends northward toward the northern baulk. It seems that this surface line also continues into the northern baulk in the area between walls 7154 and 7163 where subsurface fill 7196 was excavated last week. This means that this surface was missed in excavation of 7196.

Thus in order to uncover this surface, L7203 and L7205 in the northwest corner of the trench were both closed and below them subsurface fill 7215 was opened and excavated. 7215 is a light brown (7.5 YR 6/4) medium to coarse highly compacted angular sandy clay fill with <5cm pebbles, clay clumps and mud brick slump, possibly from wall 7202. This surface is minimally bonded with wall 7202 on its northern side. Surface 7220 is better preserved on its eastern side and sees some animal burrowing and ashy inclusions on the more western end.

Last, wall stub 7187 was finally removed along with subwall fill 7216, a brown (7.5 YR 4/4) medium to coarse textured fill with a medium compaction level and up to 5cm clay clumps. Very little cultural material came from either one of these loci.
